Target group:
The course consists of three types of modules:
1) from regional science modules consisting of seminars on politics and society in Greater China and Japan \; 
2) from social science modules, in which lectures and seminars provide the analytical tools to deal with the target regions \;
3) Specialist modules, in which the specialist language Chinese or Japanese are spoken and written. The course thus offers a comprehensive overview of political and social developments in Japan and Greater China \; the investigation of internal and intraregional areas of conflict \; the analysis of regionalization and integration trends in East Asia \; systematic training in dealing with Japanese or Chinese-language sources, as well as the teaching of translation techniques and language courses

Admission requirements:
Bachelor's degree (at least 180 ECTS credits), diploma (FH, Uni.) in fields of study in which in-depth knowledge and methodical-practical skills in the field of landscape studies and ecology, knowledge of sustainable use, planning and protection of the cultural landscape and its resources as well as knowledge in nature conservation are taught, such as: 
–\tLandscape conservation and planning, landscape architecture, landscape ecology\; 
–\tEnvironmental, Town and Country Planning\; 
–\tNature conservation, environmental sciences (except environmental engineering)\; 
–\tEcology, Biology, Geoecology\; 
–\tGeography\; 
–\tAgricultural and forestry sciences, horticulture, water management\; 
–\tTeaching qualification for the aforementioned fields of science, provided that both teaching subjects from the aforementioned fields of science have been taken.
The application must include landscape and ecological knowledge to the extent of at least 30 ECTS credits from the fields of:
–\tLandscape science and landscape planning\; 
–\tEcology including knowledge of species, terrain methods especially biotope mapping\; 
–\tSustainable use and protection of cultural landscapes\; 
–\tResource protection, including nature conservation, can be demonstrated.

Professionally qualifying degree: Bachelor's degree (180 ECTS credit points), Diplom (UAS), Diplom or 1 State Examination\; 
Proof of language proficiency: according to the European reference framework with at least level B2 or comparable qualifications
Command of German for international applicants: DSH-2, B2

